                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d660">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">890G.5151/7: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister Resident in Iraq</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Knabenshue</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Baghdad</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-12-18T15:00:00+03:00"
                            >December 18, 1940—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received December 19—1:55 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>121. The following is a confidential comment on my telegram No. 122, December 18,
                    4 p.m.<note n="15" xml:id="d660fn15">
                        <hi rend="italic">Infra</hi>.</note> which will follow. While the British
                    decision may be for financial reasons it is generally believed that it is also
                    the beginning of a political and economic pressure to be increased in other
                    directions until Iraq’s attitude toward Britain becomes more cooperative.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Knabenshue</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
